This homework assignment uses the dataset from the "Malicious and Benign Websites" Kaggle project at https://www.kaggle.com/xwolf12/malicious-and-benign-websites/home (you'll need to go to that URL to get a full description of the data).

From the overview:

The project consisted to evaluate different classification models to predict malicious and benign websites, based on application layer and network characteristics. The data were obtained by using different verified sources of benign and malicious URL's, in a low interactive client honeypot to isolate network traffic. We used additional tools to get other information, such as, server country with Whois.

In this assignment, you will perform three tasks, each worth 10 points (specific point allocations are provided for each task).

Here I picked a random number to cluster the data. When using the value 4 for n_clusters I got a silhouette score of 0.346081730394139. I want get the optimal K value by finding the highest possible silhouette score. In the next part I will use different values of K, and calculate the different silhouette scores, so I can find the optimal value of K.

b) Examine the silhouette scores for multiple values of K, and report the optimal value of K (3 points).¶

1) Examine the silhouette scores for different values of K, and report the optimal value of K¶

In [19]:
def create_dic(df): 
    d = {} 
    for k in range(3,50): 
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k) # start with 3 clusters
        kmeans.fit(df)
        score = metrics.silhouette_score(df,kmeans.labels_)
        d[k] = score
    largest = list(d.keys())[0]
    for k in d:
        if d[k] > d[largest]: 
            largest = k
    return d, largest
In [20]:
d, largest = create_dic(data_nonulls_only_numerical)
In [21]:
"The optimal value of K, after testing k as 3-49, is {}. The silhouette_score is {} when k is {}.".format(largest, d[largest],largest, )
Out[21]:
'The optimal value of K, after testing k as 3-49, is 7. The silhouette_score is 0.3629587533777847 when k is 7.'
Explanation:¶

I created a function called create_dic that takes in a DataFrame as a argument, and reurns a tuple where the first element is a dictionary of k values and their silhouette scores, and the second element is an integer that represents the k value with the largest silhouette socre.

I created a range of numbers from 3 to 49, and for every number in this range I computed n_clusters with this number and found the silhouette score. In this part I use a dictionary to store the k, number of clusters, and the assiociated silhouette_score for that k mean (the k mean, number of clusters, is the key and the value is the silhouette score). Afterwards, I found the optimal value of K by finding the largest silhouette score in the dictionary. Also, I started with 3 because as we learned in class 2 as value for k would overfit the model.

By doing this, I found that the optimal value of K is 7. This value of K has a silhouette score of 0.3629587533777847. This is the largest silhouette score when testing k values, or n_clusters, from 3-49.

Below I printed all the different K values and their associated silhouette scores.

1) compute k-means on the optimal k-value¶

In [23]:
def do_kmeans(df, largest):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters= largest)
    kmeans.fit(df)
    labels = kmeans.labels_
    centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    return kmeans, labels, centers
In [24]:
kmeans, labels, centers = do_kmeans(data_nonulls_only_numerical, largest)
Explanation:¶

I created a function called dokmeans that takes two arguments: a DataFrame and the largest k-mean, an integer. Use the K mean clustering method, called Kmeans, from the module sklearn with the optimal k-value. Afterwords, use the kmeans object, returned from the method Kmeans, and use the method .fit on the obejct with the DataFrame passed into the function to compute k-means clustering. Afterwards, use the attributes labels and clustercenters on the kmeans object. The attribute labels_ returns the labels of each point, and the attribute clustercenters returns the coordinates of cluster centers.

The function do_kmeans will return a tuple with three elements in this order: kmeans (the object), labels (the kmeans labels), and the centers (the cluster centers). Below i printed out kmeans, labels, and centers.

Explanation:¶

These are going to be my hyperparameters. For n_estimators, I created a list of numbers that start at 5 and end at 40. Each number in the list will increment by 5. I created a list of max_depth to start at 2 and end at 10. Each number in the list will increment by 2. As well, i have a random_state parameter that is a list of numbers between 0 and 11. Each number in the list is incremented by 1. The list of numbers in the hyperparameters will be used/tested on the model when I use the GridSearchCV function.

Before, the model had these parameters bootstrap=True, class_weight=None, criterion='entropy, max_depth=None, max_features='auto', max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0.0, min_impurity_split=None,min_samples_leaf=1, min_samples_split=2, min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, n_estimators=10, n_jobs=None, oob_score=True, random_state=None, verbose=0, warm_start=False.

The better model has these parameters bootstrap=True, class_weight=None, criterion='entropy', max_depth=8, max_features='auto', max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0.0, min_impurity_split=None, min_samples_leaf=1, min_samples_split=2,min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, n_estimators=25, n_jobs=None, oob_score=True, random_state=3, verbose=0, warm_start=False.

By changing the max_depth from None to 8, increasing the n_estimators from 10 to 25, and changing the random_state from None to 3 a better model is formed with a higher accuracy score. I looked up the defintion of these hyperparameters in the sklearn documentation: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html. The n_estimators is the number of trees in the forest. The max_depth is the maximum depth of the tree. If the max_depth is None, then the nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than min_samples_split samples. The parameter random_state is the seed used by the random number generator. If the parameter is None, the random number generator is the RandomState instance used by np.random.

def pca_results(data, pca):
    
    # Dimension indexing
    dimensions = ['Dimension {}'.format(i) for i in range(1,len(pca.components_)+1)]
    
    # PCA components
    components = pd.DataFrame(np.round(pca.components_, 4), columns = data.keys()) 
    components.index = dimensions

    # PCA explained variance
    ratios = pca.explained_variance_ratio_.reshape(len(pca.components_), 1) 
    variance_ratios = pd.DataFrame(np.round(ratios, 4), columns = ['Explained Variance']) 
    variance_ratios.index = dimensions

    # Create a bar plot visualization
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (17,10))

    # Plot the feature weights as a function of the components
    components.plot(ax = ax, kind = 'bar')
    ax.set_ylabel("Feature Weights") 
    ax.set_xticklabels(dimensions, rotation=0)

    # Display the explained variance ratios# 
    for i, ev in enumerate(pca.explained_variance_ratio_): 
        ax.text(i-0.40, ax.get_ylim()[1] + 0.05, "Explained Variance\n %.4f"%(ev))

    # Return a concatenated DataFrame
    return pd.concat([variance_ratios, components], axis = 1)

Explanation:¶

There are many features in the dataset so I decided to use n_components of 7. This reduces the dimensions of the data down to 7. The number of dimensions should always be less than the original number of dimensions.

I then created plot that shows each of 7 principle components extracted, and how related each of the original variables is to that principle components. In other words, the plot shows how each of the components relate to each of the variables. I analyzed each of the dimensions below. I also used cumsum to display the cumulative sum for each dimension.

Dimension 1: This first dimension explains 0.5545, or 55.45 percent, of the overall variance.

- Most of the features have equal importance. Specifically, the features TCP_CONVERSATION_EXCHANGE, APP_BYTES, SOURCE_APP_PACKETS, REMOTE_APP_PACKETS, SOURCE_APP_BYTES, REMOTE_APP_BYTES, and APP_PACKETS are most highly correlated.

Dimension 2: This dimension explains 0.1576, or 15.76 percent, of the overall variance.

- URL_LENGTH and NUMBER_SPECIAL_CHARACTERS are most highly correlated in this dimension.

Dimension 3: This dimension explains 0.1265, or 12.65 percent, of the overall variance.

- URL LENGTH and NUMBER_SPECIAL_CHARACTERS are positively correlated in this dimension, and  REMOTE_IPS and DNS_QUERY_TIMES is negatively correlated.

Dimension 4: This dimension explains 0.0753, or 7.53 percent, of the overall variance.

- In dimension 4 CONTENT_LENGTH is highly correlated. This feature has significantly more importance than other features in this dimension.

Dimension 5: This dimension explains 0.0441, or 4.41 percent, of the overall variance.

- DIST_REMOTE_TCP_PORT is highly positively correlated in this dimension.

Dimension 6: This dimension explains 0.0329, or 3.29 percent, of the overall variance.

- REMOTE_IPS is highly positively correlated in this dimension, and DNS_QUERY_TIMES is highly negatively correlated.

Dimension 7: This dimension explains 0.0046, or 0.46 percent, of the overall variance.

- URL_LENGTH feature is highly positively correlated in this dimension, and the NUMBER_SPECIAL_CHARACTERS feature is highly negatively correlated.

c) Report the optimal number of reduced dimensions based on a scree plot (2 points). Explain and justify your choice.¶

  • look at elbow
In [103]:
plt.plot(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
plt.xlabel('number of components')
plt.ylabel('cumulative explained variance')
plt.title("Screeplot")
plt.show()
Explanation:¶

A screeplot uses PCA components to find the component giving the last substantial drop in variance. This is a point of inflection, and it is where you can see an elbow on the graph. In other words, when examining the graph you should look for where there is a shift to a much shallower angle. The point of inflection looks to be 1 on the screeplot. This means 1 should be used as the principle components because there is a bend at this number on the graph. Therefore, the optimal number of dimensions is 1 based on this screeplot.
